    <custom_item>
      type        : FILE_CHECK
      description : "WG270 A22 - The web server's htpasswd files (if present) must reflect proper ownership and permissions"
      info        : "In addition to OS restrictions, access rights to files and directories can be set on a web site using the web server software.  That is, in addition to allowing or denying all access rights, a rule can be specified that allows or denies partial access rights.  For example, users can be given read-only access rights to files, to view the information but not change the files.

This check verifies that the htpasswd file is only accessible by system administrators or web managers, with the account running the web service having group permissions of read and execute.  htpasswd is a utility used by Netscape and Apache to provide for password access to designated web sites.  I"
      solution    : "The SA or Web Manager account should own the htpasswd file and permissions should be set to 550."
      reference   : "800-171|3.4.2,800-53|CM-6,8500.2|ECAN-1,CAT|II,CSCv6|3.1,CSF|PR.IP-1,ITSG-33|CM-6,NESA|T3.2.1,PCI-DSSv3.1|2.2.4,PCI-DSSv3.2|2.2.4,Rule-ID|SV-36478r2_rule,STIG-ID|WG270_A22,SWIFT-CSCv1|2.3,Vuln-ID|V-2255"
      see_also    : "https://iasecontent.disa.mil/stigs/zip/U_Apache_2-2_UNIX_V1R11_STIG.zip"
      file        : "/usr/bin/htpasswd"
# Note: Variable @APACHE_USER@ replaced with "Web Manager account" in field "owner".
      owner       : "root" || "Web Manager account"
      mask        : "227"
    </custom_item>

    <custom_item>
      type        : FILE_CHECK
# Note: Variable @HTTPD_CONFIG_DIRECTORY@ replaced with "/etc/httpd/conf" in field "description".
      description : "WG280 - The access control files are owned by a privileged web server account - /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf"
      info        : "This check verifies that the key web server system configuration files are owned by the SA or Web Manager controlled account. These same files which control the configuration of the web server, and thus its behavior, must also be accessible by the account which runs the web service. If these files are altered by a malicious user, the web server would no longer be under the control of its managers and owners; properties in the web server configuration could be altered to compromise the entire server platform."
      solution    : "The site needs to ensure that the owner should be the non-privileged web server account or equivalent which runs the web service; however, the group permissions represent those of the user accessing the web site that must execute the directives in .htacces."
      reference   : "800-171|3.4.2,800-53|CM-6,8500.2|ECCD-1,8500.2|ECCD-2,CAT|II,CSCv6|3.1,CSF|PR.IP-1,ITSG-33|CM-6,NESA|T3.2.1,PCI-DSSv3.1|2.2.4,PCI-DSSv3.2|2.2.4,Rule-ID|SV-6880r1_rule,STIG-ID|WG280,SWIFT-CSCv1|2.3,Vuln-ID|V-2256"
      see_also    : "https://iasecontent.disa.mil/stigs/zip/U_Apache_2-2_UNIX_V1R11_STIG.zip"
# Note: Variable @HTTPD_CONFIG_DIRECTORY@ replaced with "/etc/httpd/conf" in field "file".
      file        : "/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf"
# Note: Variable @APACHE_USER@ replaced with "Web Manager account" in field "owner".
      owner       : "root" || "Web Manager account"
      mask        : "117"
# Note: Variable @APACHE_GROUP@ replaced with "WebAmins" in field "group".
      group       : "root" || "WebAmins"
    </custom_item>

